<DocsLayout
  title="Introduction"
  section="Getting started"
  description="wordink is a document editor you copy into your codebase — aiming to do everything Google Docs and Microsoft Word can do, as source you own."
>
  <p>
    wordink is a <strong>document editor</strong> you copy into your codebase
    — aiming to do everything Google Docs and Microsoft Word can do, as
    source code that lives in your repo.
  </p>

  <p>
    It's built on the browser's native <code>contentEditable</code> attribute
    and the Selection / Range API — nothing more. No ProseMirror schema. No
    custom document model. No virtual DOM for the editor surface. The output
    is plain HTML.
  </p>

  <p>
    It's <strong>headless</strong>: the editor ships behaviour, you ship UI.
    The provided toolbar primitives are optional — you can mount the editor
    without any toolbar and call commands directly from your own UI. Drop the
    source files into your project, theme them with CSS variables, and the
    editor lives inside your design system instead of beside it.
  </p>

  <p>
    See the <a href="/">homepage capabilities matrix</a> for the full list of
    document features — shipped today and on the roadmap.
  </p>

  <h2>Philosophy</h2>

  <p>
    Most rich-text editors are libraries you depend on. wordink is a folder
    you own.
  </p>

  <p>
    When you run <code>npx wordink add editor</code>, the source files land in
    <code>src/components/editor/</code> in your project. From that moment, the
    code is yours. You read it. You modify it. You delete the parts you don't
    want. There's no opaque dependency tree to fight when you need to change a
    behaviour.
  </p>

  <p>This is the Shadcn model applied to rich text editing.</p>

  <h2>What's included</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Core editor</strong> — contentEditable surface with selection
      capture, command dispatch, undo/redo, paste sanitisation, keyboard
      shortcuts.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Toolbar primitives</strong> — headless components for buttons,
      dropdowns, color pickers, separators.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Shipped plugins</strong> — link, image (URL), color picker, font
      family / size, alignment, lists, code blocks, quotes.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Design tokens</strong> — every color, font, and radius is a CSS
      variable.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Who this is for</h2>

  <p>Use wordink if you want:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>A rich text editor that fits your design system perfectly</li>
    <li>Full control over the editor's behaviour without writing one from scratch</li>
    <li>To ship the smallest possible bundle (only the parts you use)</li>
    <li>To learn how a rich-text editor works by reading code that's right there</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Use something else (Tiptap, Lexical, Slate) if you want:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Collaborative editing with operational transforms or CRDTs</li>
    <li>A schema-validated document model with custom node types</li>
    <li>To never look at editor source code</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>

  <p>
    <a href="/docs/installation">Install wordink</a> in your project — five files,
    one command.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
